The chasm which separates the Aeneid from the Iliad and Odyssey is undoubtedly one which is not easily spanned. It is true that sufficient account has not always been taken of the numerous intervening objecta which break the distance and afford resting-plaoes to the eye. The substance of the Homerio poetry, the conductos the action and the conception of the actore, came to Virgil modified by the intermediate agency of the Greek drama. His view of the form may have been similarly affected by the example of those later Greek epics of which the poem of Apollonius is the only surviving specimen, and by the pre- cepts of that critical fraternity of which the author of the Argonautica was no undistingnished member. To a modern reader the exactness of the parallel only serves to make the contrast deeper and more unmistakable.
